summary.seg:
The manuscript B.8.10 is composed of two parts, both on paper. They are not contemporary, but have been bound together because they both two texts by Origen of Alexandria. The first part is a witness to the Commentary on St Matthew, together with the manuscript München, Bayerische Staatsbibliothek (BSB), Cod.graec. 191. It was used by
Erasmus of Rotterdam (1466-1536) Erasmus, Desiderius, -1536 for his 1527 edition and by Pierre Daniel Huet (1630-1721) Huet, Pierre-Daniel, 1630-1721 for his 1685 edition.

The second part is the sole witness to the whole text of treatise De oratione (Περὶ εὐχῆς) by Origen (another copy - Paris, Bibliothèque nationale de France, grec 1788 - which dates to the 15th century, contains only the final part of the text). Trinity MS B.8.10 was the exemplar for another manuscript: Paris, Bibliothèque nationale de France, Supplément grec 534 . This manuscript was copied by P.D. Huet in Stockholm in 1652, the exemplar having been brought there in 1648 by Isaac Vossius (1618-1689). Huet published the editio princeps in 1686. The manuscript is therefore identified as the codex Holmiensis, as on f. [ii] recto. (left cover, inner with classmark in red pencil, and [i] recto blank are not imaged).

supportDesc.foliation: [i-ii] + 1-214 | 215-252 + [iii-iv]. Modern foliation in pencil in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right corner.

condition.p: In fair condition, f. [ii] is detached, ff. 1 and 215 have some reinforcing paper-strips glued on. Moisture stains, traces of mould and wormholes are present throughout the manuscript.

binding.p: Couched-laminate boards covered with brown leather, edges are tooled in blind. False bands tooled in gold and red leather strip with title on spine: Origenis in Mattheum M.SS..

history.provenance: John Grant (1998, pp. 55-59) has shown that the two parts were not bound together before the 17th century.

provenance.p: According to Pierre D. Huet (cf. Koetschau (1899), p. lxxxiii-iv), when the Worms library was plundered during the Thirty Years' War, a certain Rumf, physcian to Elizabeth, Queen of Bohemia, managed to buy the manuscript from a soldier. The physician then sold it at The Hague to Isaac Vossius (1618-1689) Vossius, Isaac, 1618-1689 in the mid 1640s. In 1648 Vossius took it with him to Stockholm and entered the Royal Library. After the abdication of Queen Christina (1654), Vossius regained possession of the manuscript and later gave it to Herbert Thorndike.

history.acquisition: The manuscript was donated to Trinity College in 1670 by Thorndike, Herbert, 1598-1672 Herbert Thorndike (1598-1672) , Fellow of the College, as stated on f. [ii] verso: Ex dono Reverendi clarissimique viri Herbeti Thorndike hujusce Collegij quondam Socij. Anno Domini 1670.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws on M.R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College, Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1900), vol. 1, pp. 253-254.

collation.p:
The part consist of 27 quaternions:
Quires 1-268 ff. 1-208
Quire 278-2 ff. 209-214

signatures.p: Quire signatures in black ink, in Greek numerals, on lower margin of the last folio recto of quires 1-26 from αʹ (f. 8v) to κϛʹ (f. 208v); this is missing for quire 2 and two supplementary signatures are present on quire 3, f. 17r (τρίτον) on the lower margin and on quire 26, f. 201r (κϛʹ) on the upper right-hand corner. The signatures continue on Part II.

collation.signatures: Bifolium signatures, a-c, f-z, aa-cc, accompanied by Arabic numerals, under the last line of text on the first four recto folios of quires; "z" is repeated on quires 23 and 24 (ff. 177r-180r, 185r-188r). These signatures are missing on quires 4 and 5, but continue on Part II. On quire 1-3 a diffent hand has numbered the second half of quires (b5, b6, etc. "c8" on f. 24r is missing); from f. 24r to 54r leaves are numbered in Arabic numerals (8-38), along with the bifolium signatures on quires 6 (f) and 7 (g).

handNote.p: This part is written in a mixed minuscule script of the 14th century, upright or slanting slightly to the right, in black ink. There is only moderate variation in letter size, but enlarged beta and, less frequently, zeta are in use. Syllabic abbreviations are rare and present in the end of the lines and in the last lines of folios. Mute iota is not present, many letters, as gamma, eta or kappa, are often in majuscule.
Punctuation includes the middle and upper point and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: Decorated rope motif headpieces in red ink on ff. 1r, 75v, 96r, 117v.
Small palmette in red ink on ff. 41v, 44r, 47v, 59v, 82v, 99v, 150v, 171r
Decorated major initials in red ink on ff. 1r, 3r, 4v, 7v, 42v, 44r, 59v, 61v, 80v, 96r, 117v, 148r. Minor initial in red ink throughout the part.

additions.p: f. [ii] recto: notes identifying the manuscript as the one used by Pierre Daniel Huet (1630-1721) Huet, Pierre-Daniel, 1630-1721 , and on donation from Isaac Vossius (1618-1689) Vossius, Isaac, 1618-1689 to Thorndike, Herbert, 1598-1672 Herbert Thorndike (1598-1672) by a later hand.

history.origin: This part was copied in the 14th century.

provenance.p: In the prefatory letter to his edition of the Commentary on St Matthew (1527), Erasmus of Rotterdam (1466-1536) Erasmus, Desiderius, -1536 states that this part of the manuscript (which was then not yet bound together with the second part) was given to him on loan from the library of the castle of Ladenburg (near Heidelberg), which belonged to Heinrich von der Pfalz (1487-1552), Count Palatine and bishop of Worms Heinrich von der Pfalz Bischof von Worms, Utrecht und Freising .
